*R4.* List four access technologies. Classify each one as home access, enterprise  access, or wide-area wireless access. 

_home access: DSL (Digital Subscriber Line), FTTH (Fiber to the home)_

_enterprise: Ethernet_

_wide-area wireless: 5G_

*R5.* Is HFC transmission rate dedicated or shared among users? Are collisions  possible in a downstream HFC channel? Why or why not? 

_It is shared. They would be possible if HFC transmission didn't employ a distributed multiple access protocol to avoid collisions._

*R6.* What access network technologies would be most suitable for providing  internet access in rural areas? 

_Satellite radio channels or wide-area wireless access_

*R7.* Dial-up modems and DSL both use the telephone line (a twisted-pair copper  cable) as their transmission medium. Why then is DSL much faster than dialup access?

_DSL uses different frequencies for voice and internet data. This separation allows for faster transfer of data._

*R8.* What are some of the physical media that Ethernet can run over? 

_Twisted-pair copper wire, fiber optics_

*R9.* HFC, DSL, and FTTH are all used for residential access. For each of   these access technologies, provide a range of t ransmission rates and   comment on whether the transmission rate is shared or dedicated. 

_DSL: downstream 24-52 Mbs, upstream 3.5-16 Mbs, dedicated_

_HFC: downstream 40 Mbs - 1.2 Gbs, upstream 30 Mbs - 100 Mbs, shared_

_FTTH: downstream and upstream rates are measured in Gbs, more commonly shared_

*R10.* Describe the different wireless technologies you use during the day and their  characteristics. If you have a choice between multiple technologies, why do  you prefer one over another? 

_WiFi (mine is 90 Mbs), 4G (up to 60 Mbs), Bluetooth (about 1 Mbs). I prefer using WiFi over 4G when the network is known and trusted. It is usually faster and cheaper. I use Bluetooth when connecting my wireless devices._
